→1.2.3t4.5.6←@

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Multi-IP "find the password" puzzle. The `t` SPLIT spawns a
  child going west; the parent continues east. Each side pushes
  digits and prints them. After bouncing off `←` and `→` the two
  IPs converge on the `t` cell and merge with direction sum
  (0,0) → both die, halting the program. The trailing `@` is
  never reached.

  Output: 1 2 4 3 5 2 6 1 5 2

  Tick-by-tick (P = parent, C = child):

    t   P 위치/액션          C 위치/액션          output
    --  -------------------- -------------------- ------
     1  (0)  →  east
     2  (1)  push 1
     3  (2)  . print 1                              1
     4  (3)  push 2
     5  (4)  . print 2                              2
     6  (5)  push 3
     7  (6)  t SPLIT — child spawns at (5) west, empty stack
     8  (7)  push 4 → P[3,4]   (5) push 3 → C[3]
     9  (8)  . print 4         (4) . print 3        4 3
    10  (9)  push 5 → P[3,5]   (3) push 2 → C[2]
    11  (10) . print 5         (2) . print 2        5 2
    12  (11) push 6            (1) push 1
    13  (12) ← set west        (0) → set east
    14  (11) push 6            (1) push 1
    15  (10) . print 6         (2) . print 1        6 1
    16  (9)  push 5            (3) push 2
    17  (8)  . print 5         (4) . print 2        5 2
    18  (7)  push, move w→(6)  (5) push, move e→(6) — collision

  Both IPs land on cell (6) (the `t` cell itself) at end of t18.
  Direction sum (-1,0) + (1,0) = (0,0) → axis-clip → both die.
  No survivors → program halts cleanly. Exit 0.

  Things to notice:
    - The `@` at (13) is dead code — never executed.
    - `t` fires only once (t7). When the IPs return to it at t18
      they collide BEFORE re-executing it, so no new IPs spawn.
    - Single-IP languages (Befunge etc.) cannot express this
      pattern: the answer requires interleaving prints from two
      IPs that traverse the same row in opposite directions
      simultaneously.
